"1543":"1543","1530":"1530","1596":"1596","1562":"1562","1509":"1509","about 1530":"about 1530","Burslem, Staffordshire, England":"Burslem, Staffordshire, England","Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, England, United Kingdom","England":"England","Burslem, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Burslem, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom","Burslem, Stoke-on-Trent district, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Burslem, Staffordshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Rowley","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from one or more of various places called Rowley or Rowly, such as Rowley Regis (Staffordshire), Rowley (Devon, Durham), Rowleygreen Farm (Hertfordshire), Rowly (Surrey), Rowley (East Yorkshire), Rowley, near Bardsey (Yorkshire), Rowley in Lepton (Yorkshire), and Rowley Hill (Essex). The placenames probably all derive from Old English <i>rūh</i> ‘rough’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’, though the East Yorkshire place may have been named with <i>hlāw</i> ‘mound, hill’ as the second element.","Irish: from <b>Ó Roghallaigh</b>, a variant of <b>Ó Raghailligh</b>. See   Riley   and   O'Reilly  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Rowlee","meanings":["English: variant of   Rowley  ."]},{"name":"Roley","meanings":["English: variant of   Rowley  . This surname is now rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Rollie","meanings":["English, Scottish, and Irish: variant of   Rowley  ."]},{"name":"Riley","meanings":["English (Lancashire and Yorkshire): habitational name chiefly from High Ryley in Accrington (Lancashire) and Riley in Kirkburton, which was in the manor of Wakefield (Yorkshire). In some cases the name may derive from Riley Farm in Eyam (Derbyshire), Royley in Royton (Lancashire), or Rylah in Scarcliffe (Derbyshire). The placenames all come from Old English <i>rȳge</i> ‘rye’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’.","Irish: from <b>Ó Raghailligh</b> ‘descendant of <i>Raghailleach</i>’, Old Irish <i>Roghallach</i>. This is the name of a chieftain family in Cavan, related to the O'Rourkes. In Anglicized form it has also been confused with <b>Ó Raithile</b> found in Munster, usually Anglicized as <b>O'Rahilly</b> or   Rahilly  . See   O'Reilly  ."]},{"name":"Rolley","meanings":["English and Irish: variant of   Rowley  ."]}]},{"name":"Joan","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Contracted form of Old French <i>Jo(h)anne</i>, from Latin <i>Io(h)anna</i> (  see  Joanna  ). In England this was the usual feminine form of   John   from the Middle English period onwards and was extremely popular, but in the 16th and 17th centuries it steadily lost ground to   Jane .  It was strongly revived in the first part of the 20th century, partly under the influence of  George Bernard Shaw's  play St Joan (  1923 ), based on the life of  Joan of Arc  (  1412–31 ). Claiming to be guided by the voices of the saints, she persuaded the French dauphin to defy the occupying English forces and have himself crowned, and she led the French army that raised the siege of Orleans in  1429 . The following year she was captured by the Burgundians and sold to the English, and a year later she was burned at the stake for witchcraft at the age of 18 or 19. Her story has captured the imagination of many writers, and she is variously portrayed as a national and political hero, a model of apolitical straightforwardness and honesty, and a religious heroine. She was canonized in  1920 . More recent influences have included the American film actress  Joan Crawford  (  1908–77 , born  Lucille le Sueur ), the British actress  Joan Collins  (  b. 1933 ), the American comedienne  Joan Rivers  (  b. 1933 ), and the West Indian pop singer  Joan Armatrading  (  b. 1950 )."],"variants":[{"name":"John","meanings":["form of   John  , also used quite frequently in the English-speaking world. In Northern Ireland it is sometimes found as a variant of   Ewan ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Joan Rowley was born about 1490, in Burslem, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom, her father, John Rowley, was 42 and her mother, Gylian, was 42. She married Thomas Burslem about 1507, in Burslem, Staffordshire, England. They were the parents of at least 3 sons and 1 daughter. She died in 1594, in Shropshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 105."},"et":{"about 1490–1594":"umbes 1490–1594","1490–1594":"1490–1594","1482–1555":"1482–1555","1509–1562":"1509–1562","1511–1596":"1511–1596","1530–Male":"1530–Surnud","1543–1610":"1543–1610","1450–1489":"1450–1489","1450–Female":"1450–Surnud","about 1490":"umbes 1490","27 March 1562":"27. märts 1562","1594":"1594","1450":"1450","1482":"1482","1490":"1490","after 1489":"pärast 1489","about 1507":"umbes 1507","1511":"1511","1555":"1555","1489":"1489","1610":"1610","1543":"1543","1530":"1530","1596":"1596","1562":"1562","1509":"1509","about 1530":"umbes 1530","Burslem, Staffordshire, England":"Burslem, Staffordshire, England","Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"England","Burslem, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Burslem, Staffordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Burslem, Stoke-on-Trent district, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Burslem, Staffordshire, England"},"fi":{"about 1490–1594":"noin 1490–1594","1490–1594":"1490–1594","1482–1555":"1482–1555","1509–1562":"1509–1562","1511–1596":"1511–1596","1530–Male":"1530–Kuollut","1543–1610":"1543–1610","1450–1489":"1450–1489","1450–Female":"1450–Kuollut","about 1490":"noin 1490","27 March 1562":"27. maaliskuuta 1562","1594":"1594","1450":"1450","1482":"1482","1490":"1490","after 1489":"1489 jälkeen","about 1507":"noin 1507","1511":"1511","1555":"1555","1489":"1489","1610":"1610","1543":"1543","1530":"1530","1596":"1596","1562":"1562","1509":"1509","about 1530":"noin 1530","Burslem, Staffordshire, England":"Burslem, Staffordshire, England","Shropshire, Englan